Visualizing Covid-19 Data for Major European Economies¶

Reading time: ~15 min

Introduction¶

Dear reader,

In this notebook, you will get to explore the insights I found analyzing Covid-19 data. The goal of this project is to turn raw numbers into meaningful visual representations, discuss them, and derive conclusions. The project is mainly focused on the major European economies, although some of the derivations are applicable to other countries as well. There are multiple ways to present the same pieces of data, so the work you are reading may partially reflect my personal view of the topic. Anyway, I hope reading this notebook will improve your understanding of the Covid-19 pandemic, and let you learn something new and useful.

The notebook is structured the following way:¶

Section 3: Discussion of the results
Section 4: Conclusion

Section 1: Extracting and processing the data¶

Description¶

In this section, you will be able to see the code used to extract and process the data. The code isn't tailored for any specific country and can be used to extract and process any Covid-19 data from the given sources. Data¶

This project primarily uses two resources to access the data:

  • For time series analysis, the data is extracted from the Covid19api kindly provided by the Johns Hopkins CSSE.
  • For static analysis, the data is accessed through the NovelCOVID API.

Both APIs are recommended by the Postman COVID-19 API Resource Center.

Functions¶

Function timeSeriesInstructions() is used to view the instructions for the Johns Hopkins CSSE API. It doesn't take any arguments and returns Pandas dataframe with the instructions.

In [4]:
def timeSeriesInstructions():
    
    r = requests.get('https://api.covid19api.com/')
    instructions_dic = r.json()
    instructions = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(instructions_dic).transpose()
    
    return instructions

Function filterDate(data, start_date, end_date) accepts time series dataframe and a date range, and truncates the data with respect to the specified period. Feel free to change the inputs of this function to alter the date range.

In [5]:
def filterDate(data, start_date = '2020-03-01', end_date = '2020-05-07'):
    
    filter_start_date = data['Date'] >= start_date
    filter_end_date = data['Date'] <= end_date
    data = data[filter_start_date & filter_end_date]
    
    return data

Function timeSeriesData(list_countries) accepts a Python list with country names and returns grouped time series data for the selected countries. Before changing the inputs of this function, please familiarize yourself with the Covid19api instructions.

In [6]:
def timeSeriesData(list_countries = ['italy', 'spain', 'france']):

    data = []

    for country in list_countries:
        r = requests.get(f'https://api.covid19api.com/country/{country}')
        data_dic = r.json()
        raw_data = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data_dic)

        filter_province = raw_data['Province'] != ''
        raw_data.drop(index = raw_data[filter_province].index, inplace = True)

        filter_columns = ['CountryCode', 'Province', 'City', 'CityCode', 'Lat', 'Lon', 'Active']
        raw_data.drop(columns = filter_columns, inplace = True)

        raw_data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(raw_data['Date'], format = '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ')
        
        numeric_columns = ['Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered']
        raw_data[numeric_columns] = raw_data[numeric_columns].apply(pd.to_numeric)

        data.append(raw_data)

    data = pd.concat(data)

    column_names = ['Country', 'Date', 'Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered']
    data = data.reindex(columns = column_names)

    data = filterDate(data)
    country_group = data.groupby('Country')    

    return country_group

Function pickCountry(country_group, country_name) accepts grouped dataframe and a country name and returns time series data for the selected country. Before changing the inputs of this function, please familiarize yourself with the Covid19api instructions.

In [7]:
def pickCountry(country_group, country_name):
    
    country_name = country_name.title()
    ts_data = country_group.get_group(country_name)
    ts_data.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
    
    return ts_data

Function dailyChanges(ts_data, prc = False, periods = 1) accepts time series data for a particular country and converts it into changes over time. Changes can be viewed in absolute (pct = False) or relative terms (pct = True) and over the various number of periods (e.g. to see weekly changes: periods = 7).

In [8]:
def dailyChanges(ts_data, prc = False, periods = 1):
    numeric_columns = ['Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered']
    legend_data = ts_data[['Country', 'Date']]

    if (prc):
        change_data = round(100 * ts_data[numeric_columns].pct_change(periods = periods), 2)
        change_data.replace([np.inf, np.nan], 0, inplace = True)
    else:
        change_data = ts_data[numeric_columns].diff(periods = periods)
        change_data.replace([np.inf, np.nan], 0, inplace = True)
        change_data = change_data.astype(int)

    diff_data = pd.concat([legend_data, change_data], axis = 1)
    
    upper_bound = diff_data.index[:periods]
    diff_data.drop(labels = upper_bound, axis = 0, inplace = True)
    
    diff_data.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)

    return diff_data

Function crossSectionalData() doesn't take any arguments and is used to extract cross-sectional data from the NovelCOVID API.

In [9]:
def crossSectionalData():
    
    r = requests.get('https://coronavirus-19-api.herokuapp.com/countries')
    cs_data_dic = r.json()
    cs_data = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(cs_data_dic)
    
    cs_data = cs_data.loc[1:]
    
    cs_data = cs_data.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors = 'ignore')
    cs_data.sort_values('cases', ascending = False, inplace = True)
    
    cs_data['Population (M)'] = round((cs_data['cases'] / cs_data['casesPerOneMillion']), 2)
    
    cs_data['Population (M)'].replace([np.inf, 0], np.nan, inplace = True)
    cs_data.dropna(axis = 0, subset = ['Population (M)'], inplace = True)
    
    filter_columns = ['todayCases', 'todayDeaths', 'active', 'critical', 
                      'casesPerOneMillion', 'deathsPerOneMillion', 'testsPerOneMillion']
    cs_data.drop(columns = filter_columns, inplace = True)
    
    cs_data.columns = cs_data.columns.str.title()
    cs_data.rename(columns = {'Totaltests': 'Tested'}, inplace = True)
    cs_data.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)
    
    return cs_data

Function aggregatedCrossSectionalData(number_of_countries, include_other, test_adj) is used to aggregate the data. The first argument specifies the number of countries to leave untouched. The second argument determines whether to include aggregated data into the dataframe. The third argument allows adjusting the data for testing before aggregating it.

In [10]:
def aggregatedCrossSectionalData(number_of_countries, include_other = True, test_adj = False):
    
    cs_data = crossSectionalData()
    
    if (test_adj):
        cs_data['Cases'] = cs_data['Cases'] / cs_data['Tested'] * cs_data['Population (M)']
        cs_data['Cases'].replace([np.inf, 0], np.nan, inplace = True)
        cs_data.dropna(axis = 0, subset = ['Cases'], inplace = True)
        cs_data.sort_values(by = 'Cases', ascending = False, inplace = True)
    
    lower_bound = number_of_countries + 1
    
    agg_part = cs_data.iloc[lower_bound:]
    non_agg_part = cs_data.iloc[:number_of_countries] 
    
    other_row = agg_part.sum(numeric_only=True)
    other_row['Country'] = 'Other countries'
    
    if (include_other):
        agg_data = non_agg_part.append(other_row, ignore_index=True)
    else:
        agg_data = non_agg_part
        
    return agg_data

def testTimeSeriesData():
    
    test = timeSeriesData()
    test = pickCountry(test, 'Italy')
    
    try:
        assert test['Date'].iloc[0] == datetime.strptime('2020-03-01', '%Y-%m-%d')
        assert list(test.columns) == ['Country', 'Date', 'Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered']
        assert type(test['Confirmed'].iloc[0]) == np.int64        
        print("Congrats, tests for timeSeriesData() function have been passed.")       
    except:
        print('Assertion error detected. Please, inspect timeSeriesData() function.')
        
    test_diff = dailyChanges(test, prc = False)
    test_pct = dailyChanges(test, prc = True)
    
    max_index = len(test['Confirmed']) - 1
    index = np.random.randint(low = 1, high = max_index)
    calculation_pct = round(100 * (test['Confirmed'].iloc[index]/test['Confirmed'].iloc[index-1] - 1), 2)
    if (calculation_pct == np.inf) or (calculation_pct == np.nan):
        calculation_pct = 0
        
    calculation_diff = test['Confirmed'].iloc[index] - test['Confirmed'].iloc[index - 1] 
        
    try:    
        assert calculation_pct == test_pct['Confirmed'].iloc[index-1]
        assert calculation_diff == test_diff['Confirmed'].iloc[index-1]
        print("Congrats, tests for dailyChanges() function have been passed.")        
    except:
        print('Assertion error detected. Please, inspect dailyChanges() function.')

def testCrossSectionalData():
    
    test = crossSectionalData()
    
    upper_bound = len(test['Cases']) - 1
    number_of_countries = np.random.randint(low = 0, high = upper_bound)
    
    try:
        assert list(test.columns) == ['Country', 'Cases', 'Deaths', 'Recovered', 'Tested', 'Population (M)']
        assert type(test['Cases'].iloc[0]) == np.int64
        print('Congrats, tests for crossSectionalData() function have been passed.')
    except:
        print('Assertion error detected. Please, inspect crossSectionalData() function.')
        
    test_top = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(number_of_countries, False)
    test_agg = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(number_of_countries, True)
    
    try:
        assert len(test_top['Cases']) == number_of_countries
        assert len(test_agg['Cases']) == number_of_countries + 1
        print('Congrats, tests for aggregatedCrossSectionalData() function have been passed.')
    except:
        print('Assertion error detected. Please, inspect aggregatedCrossSectionalData() function.')

Function stackPlot() creates a stack plot for Covid-19 confirmed cases.

In [15]:
def stackPlot():
    
    data = timeSeriesData(['spain', 'italy', 'france', 'germany', 'united-kingdom'])
    
    plt.style.use('seaborn-whitegrid')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8, 4)
    
    spain = pickCountry(data, 'Spain')
    italy = pickCountry(data, 'Italy')
    france = pickCountry(data, 'France')  
    germany = pickCountry(data, 'Germany')
    uk = pickCountry(data, 'United Kingdom')
    
    x_axis = spain['Date']
    
    y_axis1 = spain['Confirmed'] / 1000 
    y_axis2 = italy['Confirmed'] / 1000
    y_axis3 = france['Confirmed'] / 1000
    y_axis4 = uk['Confirmed'] / 1000
    y_axis5 = germany['Confirmed'] / 1000
    
    labels = ['Spain', 'Italy', 'France', 'United Kingdom', 'Germany']
    colors = list(design.values())
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    fig.autofmt_xdate()
    ax.stackplot(x_axis, y_axis1, y_axis2, y_axis3, y_axis4, y_axis5, labels=labels, colors = colors)
    
    handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax.legend(handles[::-1], labels[::-1], loc = 'upper left')
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(7))
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(DateFormatter('%b %d'))
    
    ax.set_title('\nCovid-19 Spread in Major European Economies\n')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of cases (in thousands)\n')
    plt.tick_params(labelright=True)
    
    plt.show()

Function dailyCases() plots the number of daily Covid-19 confirmed cases and the daily percentage increase of the total number of confirmed cases.

In [17]:
def dailyCases():

    country_list = ['spain', 'italy', 'france', 'united-kingdom', 'germany']
    colors = list(design.values())
    
    data = timeSeriesData(country_list)
    
    plt.style.use('seaborn-whitegrid')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (6, 4)
    
    for country, color in zip(country_list, colors):
        if (country == 'united-kingdom'):
            country = 'United Kingdom'
    
        ts_data = pickCountry(data, country)
        daily_cases = dailyChanges(ts_data, prc = False)
        daily_pct = dailyChanges(ts_data, prc = True)
        
        month_ago = len(daily_cases['Date']) - 30
        
        x_axis1 = daily_cases['Date'].iloc[month_ago:]
        x_axis2 = daily_cases['Date'].iloc[month_ago:]
        
        y_axis1 = daily_cases['Confirmed'].iloc[month_ago:] 
        y_axis2 = daily_pct['Confirmed'].iloc[month_ago:] 
        
        fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, ncols = 1, sharex = False)
        
        ax1.bar(x_axis1, y_axis1, color = color)
        ax2.plot(x_axis2, y_axis2, color = color)
        
        ax1.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(3))
        ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(DateFormatter('%d.%m'))
        
        ax2.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(3))
        ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(DateFormatter('%d.%m'))
        
        if (country == 'United Kingdom'):
            country = 'the UK'
        else:
            country = country.title()
        
        ax1.set_title(f'\nNew Daily Covid-19 Cases in {country}')
        ax1.set_ylabel('Number of cases')
        # ax1.tick_params(labelright = True)
        
        ax2.set_title(f'\nPercentage Increase of Covid-19 Cases in {country}')
        ax2.set_ylabel('% increase')
        # ax2.tick_params(labelright = True)
        
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
        print('***************************************************************************')

Function distributionByCountry(test_adj) displays the total number of Covid-19 confirmed cases and their distribution by country. If test_adj = True, then the distribution will be adjusted by the number of tests per million of the population.

def distributionByCountry(test_adj = False):

    data = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(7, include_other = True)
    
    if (test_adj):
        data = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(7, include_other = True, test_adj = True)
    
    r = requests.get('https://coronavirus-19-api.herokuapp.com/countries')
    summary = r.json()
    summary  = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(summary)
    total = str(summary['cases'].iloc[0])
    
    plt.style.use('seaborn')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (6, 6)
    
    slices = data['Cases']
    labels = data['Country']
    
    color = list(design.values())

    colors = ['#CFD8DC'] + color[0:2] + [color[3]] + ['#EEEEEE'] + [color[2]] + [color[4]] + ['#E0E0E0']
    
    if (test_adj):
        colors = ['#B0B0B0', '#B8B8B8', '#C0C0C0', '#C8C8C8', '#D0D0D0', '#D8D8D8', '#E0E0E0', '#A0A0A0']
    
    plt.pie(slices, labels=labels, colors = colors, startangle=90, 
            autopct='%1.1f%%', wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black'}, 
            counterclock = False, pctdistance = 0.75, textprops = {'fontsize': 12, 'fontweight': 'bold'})
    
    if (test_adj):
        plt.title(f"\nCovid-19 Distribution (adjusted by the number of tests per M pop.)*")
    else:
        plt.title(f"\nCovid-19 Distribution (out of total {total[0]},{total[1:4]},{total[4:]} cases)")
        
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    if (test_adj):
        print('*Assuming constant cases/tests ratio')

Function perMillByCountry() displays the Covid-19 data scaled by the population.

def perMillByCountry():

    data = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(7, include_other = True)
    
    europe_data = data.iloc[1:6]
    
    europe5 = europe_data.sum(numeric_only=True)
    europe5['Country'] = 'Europe(5)'
    
    europe5 = europe5.reindex(['Country', 'Cases', 'Deaths', 'Recovered', 'Tested', 'Population (M)'])
    data = data.append(europe5, ignore_index = True)
    
    new_index = [0, 8]
    
    for i in range(8):
        if (i == 0):
            continue
        new_index.append(i)

    data = data.reindex(new_index)
    
    formatting = lambda x: '{:,.0f}'.format(x) 
    data['Legend'] = data['Country'] + '\n\n' + data['Cases'].apply(formatting).astype(str) + '\ncases'
    
    plt.style.use('seaborn')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (10, 4)
    
    x_axis = np.flip(np.arange(len(data['Country'])))
    width = 0.25
    bottom = 1000
    
    y_axis1 = data['Cases'] / data['Population (M)']
    y_axis2 = data['Recovered'] / data['Population (M)']
    y_axis3 = data['Deaths'] / data['Population (M)']   
   
    plt.bar(x_axis + width, y_axis1, width = width, label = 'Confirmed')
    plt.bar(x_axis, y_axis2, width = width, label = 'Recovered')
    plt.bar(x_axis - width, y_axis3, width = width, label = 'Deaths')
    
    plt.xticks(ticks = x_axis, labels = data['Legend'])
    plt.title("\nCovid-19 Figures Scaled by the Population\n")
    plt.ylabel('# of cases per million of population\n')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    plt.show()

Function scatterByTests() depicts the correlation between the number of Covid-19 recorded cases and the number of tests performed in a country.

In [20]:
def scatterByTests():
    
    data = crossSectionalData()
    max_countries = len(data['Country'])
    
    data = aggregatedCrossSectionalData(max_countries, include_other = False)
    filter_bias = data['Tested'] == 0
    
    data.drop(index = data[filter_bias].index, inplace = True)

    plt.style.use('seaborn')
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8, 4)
    
    cases = np.log10(data['Cases'] / data['Population (M)'])
    tests = np.log10(data['Tested'] / data['Population (M)'])
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    a, b = np.polyfit(tests, cases, deg = 1)
    y = lambda x: b + a*x
    
    ax.scatter(tests, cases, edgecolor='black', c = 'lightgrey', linewidth=1, alpha=0.6)
    ax.plot(tests, y(tests), color = 'red') 

    country_list = ['Spain', 'Italy', 'France', 'UK', 'Germany']
    colors = list(design.values())
    countries_legend = []
  
    for country, color in zip(country_list, colors):
                
        filter_country = data['Country'] != country
        country_data = data.drop(index = data[filter_country].index)
        
        country_cases = np.log10(country_data['Cases'] / country_data['Population (M)'])
        country_tests = np.log10(country_data['Tested'] / country_data['Population (M)'])

        country_legend = ax.scatter(country_tests, country_cases, color = color)
        countries_legend.append(country_legend)
    

    ax.set_xticks(ticks = tests)
    ax.set_yticks(ticks = cases)

    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(1))
    ax.yaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(1))
    
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels = ['$1$', '$10$','$10^2$','$10^3$','$10^4$','$10^5$','$10^6$'])
    ax.set_yticklabels(labels = ['', '$1$', '$10$','$10^2$','$10^3$','$10^4$','$10^5$']) 

    ax.set_xlim([0.6, 6.15])
    ax.set_ylim([-0.3, 5.3])
    
    ax.set_title('\nCorrelation Between Performed Tests and Confirmed Covid-19 Cases\n')
    ax.set_xlabel('\nPerformed tests (per M pop.)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Confirmed cases (per M pop.)\n')
    
    ax.legend(countries_legend, country_list, loc = 'upper left')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    print(f'\nFigure {local_counter}.')

Analysis¶

Note: I will use the term "Europe(5)" to denote Spain, Italy, Germany, France and the United Kingdom.

Even though the pandemic has started in China, most Covid-19 cases have been recorded on the European continent. At the beginning of May 2020, only the United States was ahead of Europe(5) by the number of confirmed Covid-19 cases. Spain, Italy, Germany, France, and the United Kingdom were severely hit by the pandemic, although their disease development patterns were not completely identical. Currently, Europe(5) counts more than a million Covid-19 recorded cases. The stack plot (Figure 1) shows the distribution of the Covid-19 cases among the above-mentioned countries. Throughout March the trend yielded exponential growth and then in early April turned concave. The inflection point took place several weeks after the preventive measures have been introduced.

In [22]:

Figure 1.

All Europe(5) countries have followed a similar pattern in terms of recorded Covid-19 cases (Figure 2). The curves differ mainly by timing and smoothness, which could be due to the actual start of the pandemic, testing capacity, and reporting quality in each country. At the moment, Spain and Italy are showing larger numbers, but the momentum seems to be the largest for the United Kingdom. However, when it comes to the Covid-19 death rate, Germany is having much lower figures than other Europe(5) countries (difference by the factor of 4). This could be due to a better healthcare system, larger testing capacity and/or absence of post-morterm testing in Germany. The Wall Street Journal provides a more detailed discussion of the topic.

The number of daily confirmed Covid-19 cases is gradually decreasing for Europe(5) countries except for the United Kingdom, where the number of recorded daily infections remains constant (Figure 3). But most importantly, it seems that all Europe(5) countries have overcome the stage of exponential growth as the percentage of new Covid-19 cases has gradually declined over time.

Figure 3.

Cumulatively, Europe(5) accounts for more than a quarter of all Covid-19 confirmed cases worldwide (Figure 4). One may think that each of the European countries separately is far behind the United States, as the latest alone accounts for more than a third of worldwide Covid-19 cases. This conclusion doesn't seem as obvious if we make a comparison in relative terms (Figure 5). When scaled by the population, the US isn't as far ahead of the European countries in terms of recorded infections and certainly isn't ahead in terms of deaths caused by Covid-19.

Figure 5.

Lastly, a reasonable question arises: "Why has the pandemic affected developed countries and Europe(5) in particular, more than the developing world?". A possible answer is: "It has not.". It seems that there is a strong correlation between the number of recorded Covid-19 cases and the number of conducted tests (Figure 6). So far, Europe(5) has been testing extensively, while the developing countries mostly have not. Therefore, the developing world figures could be just a fraction of the actual Covid-19 figures out there. We can plot the distribution adjusted for testing derived based on the assumption that the cases/tests ratio stays constant (Figure 7). Most probably, the true unbiased Covid-19 distribution is somewhere in between the two distributions we have seen so far.

Section 4: Conclusion¶

Summary¶

In this notebook, we have accessed, processed, and visualized Covid-19 data. The main tools used were Pandas and Matplotlib. The analysis was focused on five major European economies: Spain, Italy, France, Germany, and the United Kingdom. The selected time period was from 2020-03-01 until 2020-05-07.

Main takeaways¶

Note: I will use the term "Europe(5)" to denote Spain, Italy, Germany, France and the United Kingdom

  • Europe(5) countries have been all severely hit by the pandemic
  • Covid-19 development has followed similar, yet distinguishable patterns in Europe(5) countries
  • Germany has had a significantly lower death rate compared to other Europe(5) countries
  • Seemingly, Europe(5) has exited the stage of exponential infection growth
  • The disease spread in Europe(5) countries is comparable with the one in the United States
  • The distribution of Covid-19 cases could be biased due to weaker testing in the developing countries
